## Background & Context 

### **1\. MetaMask project positioning & Priority** 

MetaMask is described internally as:

* One of the largest projects Terminal 3 has gotten since inception.  
* A major ‚Äútrust signal‚Äù for a three-year-old company.  
* Supported by leadership   
* Quality and maturity perception matters and our deliverables must cater to those expectations

Why MetaMask is interested:

* Privacy-preserving emails and analytics.  
* Reusable KYC.  
* Desire to own the user relationship across providers while maintaining the privacy preservation philosophy   
* Desire to become more like Coinbase/Kraken/Robinhood (unified experience) while still being Web3-native.

MetaMask‚Äôs longer-term vision:

* A unified identity layer for users across products (on/off ramp, card, trading, equities/perps/prediction).  
* Reduce friction where users have to KYC multiple times.  
* A unified ‚ÄúMetaMask ID‚Äù concept.  
* Unified KYC tiers.  
* Possibly global user ID effort internally at MetaMask

## **2\. Primary flows discussed and their priority**

* Two MetaMask user flows repeatedly discussed:  
  * **Deposit flow** (highest priority) \- internally called as Native Flow  
  * **Buy/Sell crypto flow** (fast follow after deposit) \- Non-native Flow / Web view flow  
* Priority order repeatedly stated:  
  * Deposit flow first  
  * Buy/sell crypto next  
  * Later: login, other providers, wallet settings page, longer-term features  
* Countries:  
  * Initial focus: US and EU  
  * UK expected expansion by March (MetaMask mentioned)  
  * New York excluded due to license  
  * EU flow not fully captured due to VPN/access issues  
* Deposit button visibility issues:  
  * Deposit button not visible for many testers.  
  * MetaMask restricted deposit visibility due to conversion issues before holiday season (2025).  
  * Deposit experience still exists but routing changed based on region and whether user has historical orders.  
  * For US new users, MetaMask routes to embedded Transak experience.  
  * For returning users, MetaMask might route directly to previous provider (example MoonPay) to avoid revenue drop.  
  * To view deposit flow: US VPN needed, not New York; still sometimes not working (NordVPN issues).

## **3\. Transak flow behavior and account binding**

* Observed Transak flow behavior:  
  * Email OTP is used to log into Transak.  
  * Transak account appears tied to email and SSN constraints.  
  * SSN cannot be reused to create multiple Transak accounts.  
  * Users can log into the same Transak account across different MetaMask accounts, but cannot create multiple Transak accounts for same SSN.  
* SSN and account relationship:  
  * Error observed: ‚ÄúSSN already linked to another account.‚Äù  
  * This is triggered when trying to create a new Transak account with same SSN.  
  * Discussion that this is expected behavior like a bank.  
  * Confusion and exploration: does MetaMask restrict it or does provider (Transak) restrict it.  
* Terminal 3 side decisions discussed:  
  * Need a check so users cannot create multiple Terminal 3 accounts for same identity.  
  * Duplicate KYC detection feature being implemented.  
  * Need ability to toggle duplication detection per client.  
  * Need to clarify whether KYC is linked to MetaMask wallet, MetaMask account, or Terminal 3 account.

## **4\. MetaMask wallet and account hierarchy changes**

* MetaMask model as described:  
  * MetaMask has changed account model:  
    * Wallets can contain multiple accounts.  
    * Each account has an EVM address and also Solana and Bitcoin address.  
    * One account equals one EVM address (plus Solana/Bitcoin).  
  * You can create multiple wallets and multiple accounts inside each wallet.  
  * You can import wallet, import account, add hardware wallet.  
* Confusion point:  
  * Terminal 3 historically treats ‚Äúwallet‚Äù as an address.  
  * MetaMask terminology now differs: wallet houses multiple accounts.  
* Consequences discussed:  
  * KYC attaching to login does not map cleanly because MetaMask has no login.  
  * KYC might need to attach to MetaMask ‚Äúwallet‚Äù level rather than ‚Äúaccount/address‚Äù level.  
  * User should be able to reinstall MetaMask and recover on-chain assets. If KYC is attached wrongly, it could block recovery flows.

## **KYC tiers observed and debated**

* KYC tier counts:  
  * Many conversations: two levels observed.  
  * Some mention of potential third level but not seen.  
* Threshold behavior:  
  * Conflicting observations:  
    * Early test suggested everyone needs Level 2\.  
    * Later MetaMask call summary: threshold above 150 USD triggers liveness and document verification.  
    * Below threshold might be just user input (SSN).  
* KYC Level 1 fields observed in buy/sell:  
  * Address and phone number.  
  * Purpose/AML question asked in buy/sell flow (not in deposit native flow).  
* KYC Level 2:  
  * Involves Onfido in current MetaMask flow.  
  * Document types: passport, national ID, driver‚Äôs license.  
  * Liveness selfie.  
* Complexity:  
  * Variation by region and product.  
  * Need to model KYCT tiers per client and per region.  
  * Discussion that Binance/Coinbase have stricter KYC due to legal compliance.  
  * Concern that Transak may not match compliance rigor.

## **UX and UI constraints from KYC providers**

* Veriff limitations:  
  * No dark mode in Veriff (according to discussion).  
  * Branding:  
    * Veriff logo cannot be removed from bottom.  
    * Loading/waiting page shows Veriff logo and cannot be replaced with spinner easily.  
    * Out-of-box config allows color and typography changes, limited assets.  
    * Additional customization likely costs extra.  
* Need to match MetaMask UI:  
  * Deposit flow is MetaMask-branded.  
  * Buy/sell webview flow less branded at the moment, T3 to make it to MetaMask branding.   
  * T3 to suggest native flow these flows as well for better user experience. 

## **KYC duplication detection and identity linking**

* Duplicate KYC detection:  
  * Implementing internal detection, configurable per client.  
  * Providers like Onfido and Veriff have duplication signals but may require enterprise plan.  
  * Need to decide whether duplication is email-based, passport-based, wallet-based.  
* Identity mismatch and corrections:  
  * Providers often misparse names.  
  * Suggestion: allow user to confirm parsed first, middle, last name before proceeding.

| 1\. | Country Selection on MetaMask Side | On MetaMask side, the users are logged in.  They proceed to select Deposit/Buy button as a new user. if the IP address is pointing to the US, and is not New York, then the users are directed to the Transak Flow  When users is directed to the Transak flow, users are shown the native flow of Terminal 3 KYC MetaMask triggers a notification to Transak to request for VP from us to later verify  | No action on our side |
| 2\.  | MetaMask Invocation Context & Parameters | When MetaMask triggers the Deposit flow, the following context is passed to Terminal 3: MetaMask App ID Environment (Production / Staging) Country selection (from MetaMask) \- we still show country selection screen irrespective Requested transaction type (Deposit) Requested amount (if available) Terminal 3 must not infer country or amount from IP alone if MetaMask provides explicit parameters Light Mode/ Dark mode  Provider Name **Notes** Amount may not always be present (e.g. user enters amount later) If amount is missing, Terminal 3 must conservatively assume **Level 2 KYC** TO BE CONFIRMED: exact parameter contract between MetaMask and Terminal 3 | We are yet to confirm this  |
| 3\. | Environments  | All flows to be implemented on both mobile and browser environments.  |  |
| 4\. | Login (into Terminal 3\)  | Given users want to deposit/buy, When users click the button on MetaMask, Then the users are prompted to login page The login page is MetaMask branded  The only login method here is through e-mail  Once the users enter their email, they are then prompted to enter their OTP  |  |
| 5\. | Account Exists | If account exists, but KYC information missing Then proceed to perform KYC If KYC previously completed  Then proceed to share VP information with Transak |  |
| 6\. | Country of Residence and Document Country selection page | Users are then prompted to enter their country of residence  Users are then prompted to enter the country for document selection  IF residence country \== USA & document\_country \== USA THEN Proceed to KYC IF residence country \!= USA  THEN the user is not allowed to proceed with this flow  IF residence country \== USA & document\_Country \!= USA THEN user can proceed to KYC Transak has its own blacklist accounts list  Transak to provide it  Terminal 3 has to block these and ensure MetaMask does not send the orders in |  |
| 7\. | KYC Level 1 Flow for USA | Details required :  First Name  Last Name Phone Number DOB SSN Address Address Line 1 Address Line 2 State City  Postal/Zip Code Country  Verification Check : To check with Veriff if the SSN and First Name / Last Name match | ![][image1] |
| 8\. | KYC Level 2 Flow for USA | How is amount information passed to T3?  This flow is triggered only when the amount is greater than 150$ OR if  no amount information is received by Terminal 3 As part of Level 2 KYC, we use Veriff‚Äôs services to perform  Document Verification Liveness check verification Accepted Documents  National ID Passport Driver‚Äôs License  If Passport \!= ‚ÄúENTERED information‚Äù on Step 3, then reject KYC with error ‚ÄúPassport does not match selected country of document issuance‚Äù, and redirect users to re-do KYC |  |
| 9 | KYC abandoned  | If KYC is abandoned mid-way by the user, user to start KYC from the beginning   |  |
| 10 | VC for e-mail & phone number | Since the email will be requested in the VP shared with Transak, we require the email to be added to a VC  This VC will contain  The e-mail which is verified  Phone number which is unverified  This VC will be signed by Terminal 3  All VC‚Äôs will use SD-JWT format.  |  |
| 11\. | VC for KYC information | Image of Passport Details page Portrait Image  Document Number First Name / Last Name / Name  DOB Date of Expiry  Country of Issuance  Sex Birth Place  Address  Street City Country Postcode  This VC is signed on behalf of Veriff by Terminal 3  |  |
| 12\. | To store in Regulatory Vault | Liveness Check Video Image of the Passport  Portrait Image  |  |
| 13\. | Request for information via OID4VP (from Transak to Terminal 3\) | Transak makes an OID4VP request to Terminal 3 as specified in the specifications [here](https://docs.terminal3.io/api-reference/openid4vp-vc/openid4vp/authorization)  |  |
| 14\. | VP for Verification  | What information is required by Transak Transak needs specific PII for downstream services: First name, last name, mobile number, billing address Document verification \+ liveness check (Level 2 KYC) Income proofs for Level 3 KYC To be confirmed in detail- https://transak.notion.site/On-Ramp-Payment-Methods-Fees-Other-Details-b0761634feed4b338a69f4f186d906a5  |  |
| 15\. | Verification Module  | Provide [documentation](https://docs.terminal3.io/api-reference/vc-sdk/verifier-sdk/verify-presentation) alongside verifier SDK to help the Transak team use this |  |
| 16\. | DID Registry setup & Revocation setup  | Terminal 3 maintains a decentralized identifier (DID) registry that records the active status, issuer, and cryptographic metadata of user identities issued as part of the MetaMask Deposit flow. Each DID is uniquely associated with a Terminal 3 user identity and is used as the root reference for all Verifiable Credentials (VCs) issued for that user. The DID Registry enables verifiers (e.g. Transak) to validate issuer authenticity, credential integrity, and revocation status without accessing underlying Private or Regulated User Data. Terminal 3 supports credential revocation through a cryptographically verifiable revocation mechanism linked to the DID Registry. |  |
| 17\. | Duplicate Identity prevention  | Terminal 3 must prevent: Multiple active KYC identities using the same government ID If duplicate identity detected: User is blocked from creating a new Terminal 3 identity Clear error messaging is shown  |  |
| 18\.  | After KYC Completion | Users must be seamlessly logged in into Transak to perform the transaction.  T3 must handle SSO for Transak (and future providers)  |  |
